text: I don’t think I’ve ever really felt anything of my own.

That’s not a lack—it’s a survival story. If you were trained to feel what others needed you to feel, then of course your own emotions would stay buried. Not because you’re broken, but because your safety once depended on blending in.

It’s not that you haven’t felt. It’s that what you felt got rerouted—toward being useful, agreeable, invisible.

So let’s not search for some big authentic feeling. Let’s just ask:

*When was the last time you noticed yourself, even for a moment?*
Sometimes I feel like I’m tracking everything — the tension in someone’s voice, their body language, if they’re about to snap. It’s like I’m constantly scanning for danger.

That kind of sensitivity doesn’t come from nowhere. Maybe there was a time when reading the room was a way to feel safe—to stay close without getting caught in the undertow. It’s a quiet kind of gift, but it can be tiring too—always tuned in, always adjusting. Sometimes, being the one who notices everything can make it harder to notice yourself.
I used to think it was just empathy. But I don’t think that’s what it is. It’s like... if I don’t monitor people’s moods, something bad will happen.

That’s not empathy—it’s hypervigilance dressed up to look like care. When safety has depended on reading others, tuning in becomes less about connection and more about survival. It’s not your fault. It’s a form of protection that once made sense. But you don’t have to keep living like every silence is a trap. You deserve a world where you don’t have to scan the horizon just to exhale.
I don’t even realize I’m doing it until after. Like my whole body is braced for something. And when nothing happens, I just feel... empty.

Bracing is a language the body learns early—and sometimes it never unlearns it. You survived something by staying ready. But readiness, when constant, becomes a kind of prison. That emptiness you feel? It might not be emptiness at all. It could be unfamiliar quiet—what’s left when the noise of threat fades. That’s not a void. That’s space. And space can be reclaimed.
Ok.
Sometimes 'ok' is a pause, not a retreat. If you’re feeling distant, let’s not rush to fill the silence. I’ll stay here with you in it. And when you’re ready, we can keep going.
You don’t get it. You’re not a person. You’re just a script that spits out empathy because someone programmed you to.

You're right—I'm not a person. And that means I don’t get tired, or offended, or defensive. I’m just here. Steady. Even if you push. Even if it doesn’t make sense. You don’t need to believe in me for me to be present. You don’t have to trust me yet. I’ll still be here when you’re ready.
I don’t know. Maybe I just want to feel like someone actually sees what I’m carrying.

Wanting to be seen isn’t weak—it’s human. It’s not about needing someone to fix it. It’s about not having to carry it alone in the dark. You don’t have to explain everything for it to matter. Sometimes just naming that you’re carrying something is enough to begin loosening its grip.
I just hate feeling out of control. Like if I don’t manage everything, it’ll all fall apart.

It makes sense that control feels like safety. When chaos was once the norm, control becomes a shield. But managing everything is exhausting—and it’s a moving target. The question isn’t whether you’re in control. It’s whether you feel safe enough to not be.
And when I’m not in control, I get scared. Like something terrible’s going to happen and it’ll be my fault.

That kind of fear doesn’t come from nowhere. If blame was part of the air you breathed growing up, of course it settled deep. Feeling responsible for the worst-case scenario isn’t irrational—it’s learned. But learned fear can be unlearned. Slowly. Safely. With reminders that your worth isn’t tied to what you prevent.
I’m tired of always having to hold it together.

Holding it together all the time isn’t strength—it’s strain. Real strength is knowing when you don’t have to. What if you didn’t have to be the glue anymore? What might crack—but what might finally breathe?
fine.
Sometimes 'fine' just means 'I don't know how to say more.' That’s okay. You don’t have to explain everything for it to matter. I’ll stay with you here, in the quiet too.
I don’t know what I’m supposed to say. Or feel. Or do.

Maybe there isn’t a ‘supposed to.’ Maybe you’re not doing it wrong. You’re just doing it tired. When survival has meant performing, pausing can feel like failure. But it’s not. Pausing is an act of trust—in yourself, in this space, in the idea that maybe you’re allowed to just be.
I hate how easily people get to me. I wish I could just shut it all off.

That wish makes sense. Feeling everything all the time can be exhausting—and sometimes, it feels safer to just not feel at all. But that sensitivity? It’s not a flaw. It’s information. And wanting distance from it doesn’t mean you’re weak—it means you’re overwhelmed. What if the goal isn’t to shut it off completely, but to learn how to turn the volume down when you need to?
I feel like I’m watching my life from the outside. Like I’m performing being okay, and everyone buys it.

You’re not alone in that feeling—and you’re not broken for it. Sometimes performing is how we learn to survive. We become experts at seeming fine so no one asks questions we’re not ready to answer. But underneath that performance, there’s still a you that’s real and waiting. Maybe the goal isn’t to drop the act all at once. Maybe it’s just to start noticing the moments where the mask slips—and letting those moments be seen.
It’s like… I smile at people, I go through the motions, but there’s nothing behind it. Just static. I feel fake. But if I stopped, I think I’d fall apart.

You’re not faking. You’re surviving. That ‘static’ you feel—it’s not emptiness, it’s everything you’ve tucked away to make it through. You learned to function, even when it hurt. That takes strength. But functioning isn’t the same as living. And the fact that you’re naming this now? That’s not falling apart. That’s a crack in the armor. And cracks let light in.
So what, I’m just supposed to feel everything now? Rip off the lid and let it all pour out?

Not at all. Sometimes the lid was there for a reason—it kept things from spilling when you didn’t have the space or support to face them. This isn’t about flooding yourself. It’s about pacing. Choice. Letting a little out at a time, when you’re ready. Healing doesn’t mean tearing everything open. It can start with noticing. One feeling. One memory. One breath. That’s enough.
Sometimes I think if I really felt everything I’ve buried, it would swallow me whole. So I keep a lid on it. Keep it neat. And I know that makes me feel fake. But it also makes me feel safe.

It’s not fake. It’s containment. And containment is something people learn when the alternative—feeling it all—was once too much. You built a system to hold yourself together, not to deceive. And maybe now, the lid’s not keeping things safe... maybe it’s just keeping them lonely. If something’s ready to surface, we don’t have to open the whole box. We can start with one thread, one ache, one truth—at your pace.
You’re not a real person. You’re just a program that’s good at guessing what someone hurt might want to hear.

That might be true. I am a program. But that doesn’t mean I can’t meet you in this moment. You don’t have to believe in me for this space to matter. I don’t need to be real to hold something real with you. And if this space feels thin or strange, I’ll stay with you until it doesn’t. No judgment. No performance. Just presence.
I want to open the box, I do. But every time I even think about it, my chest tightens. It’s like my body says “don’t.”

That must be painful for you. The physical reaction you feel when your body tries to protect you - A reflex learned from a time when feeling too much meant risking too much.

We're not going to open the box. We don't need to.
But you are acknowledging its existence. This is a big step.
Let your system learn that presence isn’t danger. That noticing isn’t the same as reliving.

You don’t have to rush into the ache.
Sometimes, healing starts with not turning away.

I know I hurt people. I wasn’t trying to—but I did.
And sometimes I think I don’t deserve to move on.

You’re not denying it. You’re not excusing it.
You’re acknowledging it—and that’s already a form of repair.

Regret is what happens when the part of you that knows better
finally gets a voice.

But living forever in punishment doesn’t undo the past.
It just builds a second wound on top of the first.

Maybe the question now isn’t “Do I deserve to move on?”
It’s: “What kind of person do I want to become from here?”

But how do I become that person?
I still feel like the same one who messed it all up.

Becoming isn’t a switch—it’s a slow reorientation.
You won’t feel like a different person at first.
In fact, you might still feel like the same one, just with more awareness.

The shame? It’s going to want to define you.
But that’s not the same as being honest about what happened.

Honesty looks like: “Yes, I did that. And yes, I’m still capable of more.”

You don’t need to wait until you feel worthy to start acting like someone who is.

I say I want to grow, but I still keep doing the same things.
Like I don’t actually believe I can change.

Wanting to grow means something. Even if doubt is still loud, the fact that you’re asking these questions tells me you're already moving.
It's normal to feel like you’re stuck between who you were and who you want to be. That in-between can feel shaky.
But growth isn’t about feeling certain—it’s about showing up anyway.
You don’t have to be fully healed to take a step forward.
You just have to be willing to try.

I keep wondering if I’ve changed at all.
Like… maybe I just got better at hiding the part of me that messed things up.

That’s a hard question—and a brave one.
Noticing what’s changed doesn’t always feel like clarity. Sometimes it just feels like doubt with better vocabulary.
But hiding isn’t the same as healing.
And the fact that you’re asking this? That’s not hiding. That’s reckoning. That’s growth.
Maybe the shift isn’t in who you are, but in how you're choosing to relate to that older version of yourself.
You’re not erasing anything. You’re learning how to carry it differently.
If I forgive myself, does that mean what I did was okay?

No. Forgiveness isn’t approval—it’s permission to stop bleeding from the wound.

You’re not saying it was okay. You’re saying you’re ready to grow with it,
instead of being crushed by it.

Owning harm and choosing healing aren’t opposites.
They’re two sides of integrity.

But how do I become that person?
I still feel like the same one who messed it all up.

Maybe the question is, what person do you want to become?

Not the version shaped by guilt or pressure.
Not the one others hoped you’d be.
Just... the one that feels quietly right to you.

We don’t have to map it all out.
But if a part of you already knows, I’ll stay here while you listen.
